    "note": "Do remittances make economies grow? Across developing countries as a whole, the study finds essentially no average effect. The interesting result appears when the panel is narrowed to Small Island Developing States: there the association turns positive and significant, strongest for SIDS in Africa and the Pacific. The authors point to the volatility and labour markets of small economies as the reason size changes what money from away can do. The method matters as much as the result. A panel model holds trade, investment, prices, and each country's quirks still, so that what remains is the remittance effect itself, and it is the econometric case that islands are not just small versions of everywhere else.",
